The [[Bayer designation]] '''Rho Sagittarii''' ('''Rho&nbsp;Sgr''', '''ρ&nbsp;Sagittarii''', '''ρ&nbsp;Sgr''') is shared by two [[star]]s in the [[constellation]] [[Sagittarius (constellation)|Sagittarius]].
* [[Rho1 Sagittarii|ρ<sup>1</sup> Sagittarii]]<ref name=SIMBAD1/> * [[Rho2 Sagittarii|ρ<sup>2</sup> Sagittarii]]<ref name=SIMBAD2/>
The two stars are separated by 0.46° in the sky. Because they are close to the [[ecliptic]], they can be [[occulted]] by the [[Moon]] and, very rarely, by [[planet]]s. The next occultation of ρ¹ Sagittarii by a planet will take place on 23 February 2046, when it will be occulted by [[Venus]].
In [[Chinese language|Chinese]], {{lang|zh|建}} ({{lang|zh-Latn|Jiàn}}), meaning ''[[Dipper (Chinese constellation)|Establishment]]'', refers to an asterism consisting of ρ¹ Sagittarii [[Xi1 Sagittarii|ξ² Sagittarii]], [[Omicron Sagittarii|ο Sagittarii]], [[Pi Sagittarii|π Sagittarii]], [[43 Sagittarii]] and [[Upsilon Sagittarii|υ Sagittarii]]. Consequently, ρ¹ Sagittarii itself is known as {{lang|zh|建五}} ({{lang|zh-Latn|Jiàn wǔ}}, {{lang-en|the Fifth Star of Establishment}}.)<ref>{{zh icon}} [http://aeea.nmns.edu.tw/2006/0605/ap060511.html AEEA (Activities of Exhibition and Education in Astronomy) 天文教育資訊網 2006 年 5 月 11 日]</ref>
